Root nodule metabolism is highly specialized. Within the 

Alnus

infected cells, 

Frankia

is supplied with malate by the host plant (

) and exports the fixed nitrogen to the cytosol in the form of ammonia (

). The exported ammonium is assimilated and transported to the xylem mainly in the form of citrulline (

). Citrulline is the main amino acid found in roots and nodules (

; 

). Altogether, the primary metabolism in nodules is well known, while the specialized metabolites in actinorhizal nodules have yet to be characterized. As part of our ongoing phytochemical research on root nodules to provide chemical understanding of actinorhizal symbiosis (

), we investigated the constituents of 

A. cremastogyne

root nodules and identified four 3-pentanol glycosides, including three undescribed ones. In addition, the distribution of 3-pentanol glycosides was studied.

Compound 3, obtained as a colourless oil, had the molecular formula of C 17 H 32 O 10 based on pseudo-molecular ions at m/z 419 [M+Na] + in positive ESI-MS and m/z 395 [M H] in negative ESI-MS. After structure determination of 1 and 2, it was found that the 1 H and 13 C NMR spectra ( Tables 1 and 2 ) of compound 3 displayed a group of signals ( δ 10.2, 9.8, 28.2, 27.3 and 83.3) indicating the presence of 3-pentanol as well as two anomeric carbons ( δ 103.7 and 102.2) and a secondary methyl ( δ H 1.01 and δ C
18.0) indicating the presence of glucose and rhamnose. The ether linkage between 3-pentanol and glucose was the same as that in compounds 1 and 2. The glycosidic linkage between C-1 ′′ of rhamnose and C-6 ′ of glucose was assigned according to the HMBCs from H-6 ′ ( δ 3.59 and 3.96) of glucose to C-1 ′′ ( δ 102.2) of rhamnose ( Fig. 2 ). α -Rhamnose and β -glucose were confirmed on the basis of an anomeric proton doublet at δ H 4.75 with a small 3 J H-1,H-2 coupling constant (1.5 Hz) and an anomeric proton doublet at δ H 4.29 with a large 3 J H-1,H-2 coupling constant (7.8 Hz), respectively. Furthermore, acid hydrolysis (
) of compound 3 released D- glucose ( tR = 20.1 min) and L- rhamnose ( tR = 22.0 min), which were detected after derivatisation by comparison of their retention time ( tR ) with derivatively authentic D- glucose ( tR =20.3 min) and L- glucose ( tR =18.7 min) and with derivatively authentic L- rhamnose ( tR = 22.2 min) in HPLC analysis ( Fig. S2 ), respectively. Finally, compound 3 was identified as 3-pentyl α -L- rhamnopyranosyl-(1 ′′ →6 ′ )- β -D- glucopyranoside.

