After sulfuric acid hydrolysis of 

A. cremastogyne

leaves, stems, fruits, root nodules, and roots, 3-pentanol was quantified by gas chromatography mass spectrometry (GC-MS) as total content. The content of free 3- pentanol was also quantified in the samples without sulfuric acid hydrolysis, of which the results are shown in 
Fig. 3A
. The content of free 3- pentanol in root nodules and roots were 9.5 and 0.8 μmol/g (
FW
), respectively, while it was not detected in leaves, stems and fruits. The difference values between the total and free content indicated the content of 3-pentanol released from glycosides, which could be featured as the content of 3-pentanol glycosides. The results are shown in 
Fig. 3B
. The content of 3-pentanol glycosides varied greatly among the different organs. The contents of 3-pentanol glycosides in leaves, stems, fruits, root nodules, and roots were 1.0 μmol/g (
FW
), 3.5 μmol/g (
FW
), 0 μmol/ g (
FW
), 120.7 μmol/g (
FW
), and 2.6 μmol/g (
FW
), respectively. The results show that 3-pentanol glycosides are abundantly distributed in root nodules, while they are distributed in leaves, roots and stems at low level. By contrast, 3-pentanol glycosides are not detected in fruits.
